[1mNAME[0m
       toupper, tolower, toupper_l, tolower_l - convert uppercase or lowercase

[1mLIBRARY[0m
       Standard C library ([4mlibc[24m, [4m-lc[24m)

[1mSYNOPSIS[0m
       [1m#include <ctype.h>[0m

       [1mint toupper(int [4m[22mc[24m[1m);[0m
       [1mint tolower(int [4m[22mc[24m[1m);[0m

       [1mint toupper_l(int [4m[22mc[24m[1m, locale_t [4m[22mlocale[24m[1m);[0m
       [1mint tolower_l(int [4m[22mc[24m[1m, locale_t [4m[22mlocale[24m[1m);[0m

   Feature Test Macro Requirements for glibc (see [1mfeature_test_macros[22m(7)):

       [1mtoupper_l[22m(), [1mtolower_l[22m():
           Since glibc 2.10:
               _XOPEN_SOURCE >= 700
           Before glibc 2.10:
               _GNU_SOURCE

[1mDESCRIPTION[0m
       These functions convert lowercase letters to uppercase, and vice versa.

       If  [4mc[24m  is a lowercase letter, [1mtoupper[22m() returns its uppercase equivalent, if an uppercase representation exists in the current locale.  Otherwise, it
       returns [4mc[24m.  The [1mtoupper_l[22m() function performs the same task, but uses the locale referred to by the locale handle [4mlocale[24m.

       If [4mc[24m is an uppercase letter, [1mtolower[22m() returns its lowercase equivalent, if a lowercase representation exists in the current locale.   Otherwise,  it
       returns [4mc[24m.  The [1mtolower_l[22m() function performs the same task, but uses the locale referred to by the locale handle [4mlocale[24m.

       If [4mc[24m is neither an [4munsigned[24m [4mchar[24m value nor [1mEOF[22m, the behavior of these functions is undefined.

       The behavior of [1mtoupper_l[22m() and [1mtolower_l[22m() is undefined if [4mlocale[24m is the special locale object [1mLC_GLOBAL_LOCALE [22m(see [1mduplocale[22m(3)) or is not a valid
       locale object handle.

[1mRETURN VALUE[0m
       The value returned is that of the converted letter, or [4mc[24m if the conversion was not possible.

