[1mNOTES[0m
       The standards require that the argument [4mc[24m for these functions is either [1mEOF [22mor a value that is representable in the type [4munsigned[24m [4mchar[24m.  If the argu‐
       ment [4mc[24m is of type [4mchar[24m, it must be cast to [4munsigned[24m [4mchar[24m, as in the following example:

           char c;
           ...
           res = toupper((unsigned char) c);

       This  is necessary because [4mchar[24m may be the equivalent [4msigned[24m [4mchar[24m, in which case a byte where the top bit is set would be sign extended when convert‐
       ing to [4mint[24m, yielding a value that is outside the range of [4munsigned[24m [4mchar[24m.

       The details of what constitutes an uppercase or lowercase letter depend on the locale.  For example, the default [1m"C" [22mlocale does not know  about  um‐
       lauts, so no conversion is done for them.

       In some non-English locales, there are lowercase letters with no corresponding uppercase equivalent; the German sharp s is one example.

